details.purpose: For recording a narrative description and clinical interpretation of the findings observed during the physical examination of a wound.
details.use:
Use to record a narrative description and clinical interpretation of the findings observed during the physical examination of a wound.
This archetype has been specifically designed to be used in the 'Examination detail' SLOT within the OBSERVATION.exam or ACTION.procedure archetype, but can also be used within other ENTRY or CLUSTER archetypes, where clinically appropriate.
Use to provide a framework in which CLUSTER archetypes can be nested in the 'Examination findings' SLOT to record additional structured physical examination findings.
The CLUSTER.exclusion_exam archetype can be nested within the 'Examination not done' SLOT to optionally record explicit details about the examination not being performed.
Use to incorporate the narrative descriptions of clinical findings within existing or legacy clinical systems into an archetyped format, using the 'Clinical Description' data element.
details.misuse:
Not to be used to record stand-alone clinical measurements or test results - use specific OBSERVATION archetypes. For example OBSERVATION.head_circumference or OBSERVATION.glasgow_coma_scale.
Not to be used for recording the clinical history - use specific OBSERVATION and CLUSTER archetypes. For example OBSERVATION.story and CLUSTER.symptom_sign.

items.items: Findings observed during the physical examination of a wound.
Identification of the examined body system or anatomical structure.

For example: the very generic term "skin", which will likely require additional qualification using one of the 'Body site' data elements, or the complete phrase "skin of right knee". Coding of the system or structure examined with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
Narrative description of the overall findings observed during the examination of a wound.
Structured details about the wound not captured in the other fields.
Digital image, video or diagram representing the wound findings.
Single word, phrase or brief description that represents the clinical meaning and significance of the wound findings.
Coding of the 'Clinical interpretation' with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
Additional narrative about the wound findings, not captured in other fields.
Details to explicitly record that this examination was not performed.
A structured description of the area of the body under examination.
If the body site has been fully identified in the 'System or structure examined' or the 'Body site' data element, this SLOT becomes redundant.
Identification of the area of the body under examination.
For example: "entire body", "face" or "right cheek". If the body site has been fully identified in the 'System or structure examined' data element, this data element becomes redundant.
Is undermining present in the wound?
For example: color; induration; warmth; or oedema.
Details about the observation of any exposed body structures, devices, and/or foreign bodies visible by the naked eye in a wound.
Idnetification of an exposed body structure, device, and/or foreign body visible by the naked eye within the wound.
Coding of the visible internal structure if preferred, if possible.
A name or alias for a single wound, so that it can be distinguished from other wounds.
Is tunnelling present in the wound?
The identified object or structure is observed in the wound.
The identified object or structure is not observed in the wound.
It is not possible to tell if the identified object or structure is present or absent in the wound.
Narrative description about the associated factor.
Additional narrative about the associated factor, not captured in other fields.
Undermining is observed in the wound.
Undermining is not observed in the wound.
It is not possible to tell if undermining is present or absent.
Tunnelling is observed in the wound.
Tunnelling is not observed in the wound.
It is not possible to tell if a tunnel is present or absent.
Is an exudate present in the wound?
An exudate is observed in the wound.
An exudate is not observed in the wound.
It is not possible to tell if an exudate is present or absent.
The length of the wound, in the longest dimension.
The width of the wound, perpendicular to longest dimension.
Details about undermining of the wound.
Multiple occurrences of this cluster will allow recording of the undermining occurring in different parts of the wound.
Amount of tissue destruction that extends under the intact wound edge.
Direction of the undermining outward from the centre of the wound, as described by a clock-face.
Details about tunnelling into other tissues.
Multiple occurrences of this cluster will allow recording about each tunnel that leads from the wound.
Length of an identified tunnel radiating out from the centre of the wound.
Direction of the tunnel radiating outward from the centre of the wound, as described by a clock-face.
Narrative description about the edge of the wound.
The colour of the wound edge.
Details about the appearance of the base of the wound.
Multiple occurrences of this Cluster allow for recordings of multiple discrete areas of different appearances..
Description of the tissue in the wound base.
For example: necrotic; sloughing; fibrinous; eschar; or granulation tissue.
The proportion of the wound that has the identified appearance.
This is the the area of the base of the wound that has a specific appearance, compared to the total area of the wound bed and represented as a percentage.
Details about the colour of the base of the wound.
Multiple occurrences of this Cluster allow for recordings of more than one colour.
Description of the colour of the wound base.
For example: red/healthy; red/hyperaemic; pink, yellow; black, brown; or grey.
The proportion of the wound that is the identified colour.
This is the the area of the base of the wound that is a specific colour, compared to the total area of the wound bed and represented as a percentage.
Description of the skin surrounding the wound.
Narrative description about undermining of the whole wound.
Details about factors that may be associated with the wound.
Associated factor that may causing or influencing the healing of the wound.
For example: a device; a drain tube; or a pressure point.
The identified factor is not observed.
It is not possible to tell if the identified factor is present or absent.
Description of the outline of the wound.
The appearance of the edge of the wound.
The attachment of the edge to the wound base.
The edge appears flush with the wound base or has a sloping edge.
The edge has sides or walls present; floor or base of wound is deeper than edge.
Soft to firm and flexible to touch.
Callous-like tissue formation around wound & at edges.
Description of the depth of the wound.
As per Bates-Jensen wound assessment tool.
Tissues damaged but no break in skin surface
Superficial, abrasion, blister or shallow crater
Even with, &/or elevated above skin surface (e.g.,hyperplasia).
Deep crater with or without undermining of adjacent tissue
Visualization of tissue layers not possible due to necrosis
Supporting structures include tendon, joint capsule
Type of skin surrounding the wound.
Appearance of the skin around the edge of the wound.
Multiple occurrences allow for the use of coded text to describe various types of skin around the wound.
The presence of tenderness in and around the wound.
The relative temperature of the skin surrounding the wound.
May appear prior to wound opening; skin surface is white or grey.
Thin, mucinous substance; scattered throughout wound bed; easily separated from wound tissue.
Thick, stringy, clumps of debris; attached to wound tissue.
Soggy tissue; strongly attached to tissue in centre or base of wound.
Firm, crusty tissue; strongly attached to wound base and edges (like a hard scab).
